{
  "id": "7610894660566895885",
  "text": "Low sexual desire in midlife is often misunderstood, but it is not a personal failing.\n\nDuring perimenopause and menopause, changes in estrogen are only part of the physiologic transition. Testosterone levels also decline with age in women, and for some, this shift can be associated with distressing changes in sexual desire and overall wellbeing.\n\nIn this week’s episode of unPAUSED, I sit down with James Simon, MD, to discuss how clinicians and patients can approach concerns about desire with evidence-based evaluation, thoughtful risk assessment, and individualized care.\n\nThe goal of this conversation is to better understand the biology behind these changes and explore appropriate options that support quality of life.\n\nSexual health is an important component of overall health, and it deserves the same clinical attention as any other midlife transition.\n\nHead to the link in bio to listen to the full conversation. \n\n#MidlifeHealth #MenopauseCare #WomensHealth #HormoneHealth #HealthyAging ",
